# 📧 Nodemailer with OAuth2 – Node.js

This guide provides step-by-step instructions for setting up and using **Nodemailer** in a Node.js application with **OAuth2 authentication** using ClientID and ClientSecret, along with generating a refresh token using the **OAuth 2.0 Playground**.

---

## 📋 Prerequisites

- Node.js installed on your machine.
- A Google account to generate OAuth2 credentials (ClientID and ClientSecret).
- Access to the [Google API Console](https://console.developers.google.com/) to create OAuth2 credentials.

---

## 🚀 Step 1: Enable Gmail API & Create OAuth2 Credentials

1. Navigate to the [Google API Console](https://console.developers.google.com/).
2. Create a new project or select an existing one.
3. Go to the **Library** section, search for **Gmail API**, and enable it.
4. Go to the **Credentials** section.
5. Click on **Create Credentials** and choose **OAuth 2.0 Client IDs**.
6. Set the application type to **Web application**.
7. Under **Authorized redirect URIs**, add:
   - `http://localhost`
   - `https://developers.google.com/oauthplayground`
8. After creating, you'll get your **ClientID** and **ClientSecret**.

---

## 🔑 Step 2: Generate a Refresh Token using OAuth 2.0 Playground

1. Go to [OAuth 2.0 Playground](https://developers.google.com/oauthplayground).
2. Click the ⚙️ settings icon (top right) and check **Use your own OAuth credentials**.
3. Enter your **ClientID** and **ClientSecret**.
4. In the left panel, find and select `https://mail.google.com/` under Gmail API v1.
5. Click **Authorize APIs** and sign in with your Google account.
6. Click **Exchange authorization code for tokens**.
7. Copy the **Refresh Token**.

---

## 📦 Step 3: Install Dependencies
```bash
npm install nodemailer dotenv
```

---

## 🔐 Step 4: Setup Environment Variables

Create a `.env` file in your root directory:
```env
EMAIL_USER=your-email@gmail.com
CLIENT_ID=your-client-id
CLIENT_SECRET=your-client-secret
REFRESH_TOKEN=your-refresh-token
```

---

## ✉️ Step 5: Setup Nodemailer with OAuth2

Create a new file `email.js` and set up the Nodemailer transporter with OAuth2:
```js
require('dotenv').config();
const nodemailer = require('nodemailer');

const transporter = nodemailer.createTransport({
  service: 'gmail',
  auth: {
    type: 'OAuth2',
    user: process.env.EMAIL_USER,
    clientId: process.env.CLIENT_ID,
    clientSecret: process.env.CLIENT_SECRET,
    refreshToken: process.env.REFRESH_TOKEN,
  },
});

// Verify the connection configuration
transporter.verify((error, success) => {
  if (error) {
    console.error('Error connecting to email server:', error);
  } else {
    console.log('Email server is ready to send messages');
  }
});

module.exports = transporter;
```

---

## 📤 Step 6: Send Emails

In the same `email.js` file, add a function to send emails:
```js
// Function to send email
const sendEmail = async (to, subject, text, html) => {
  try {
    const info = await transporter.sendMail({
      from: `"Your Name" <${process.env.EMAIL_USER}>`, // sender address
      to,        // list of receivers
      subject,   // Subject line
      text,      // plain text body
      html,      // html body
    });
    console.log('Message sent: %s', info.messageId);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error sending email:', error);
  }
};

module.exports = { transporter, sendEmail };
```

---

## 🧪 Step 7: Use it in Your App
```js
const { sendEmail } = require('./email');

sendEmail(
  'recipient@example.com',
  'Hello!',
  'This is a plain text message.',
  '<h1>This is an HTML message</h1>'
);
```

